SIMPLE: plop
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plop
<hw>Plop</hw> <pr>(pl⟦ocr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Plopped</conjf> <pr>(pl⟦ocr⟧pt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Plopping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Imitative.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To fall, drop, or move in any way, with a sudden splash
or slap, as on the surface of water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>The body <qex>plopped</qex> up, turning on its side.</q>
<rj><qau>Kipling.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>plop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: plop
<hw>plop</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>to drop (something) so
that it makes a plopping sound; especially, to drop with the sound of
something falling into water.</def> <wns>[wns=1, 2]</wns>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To set down quickly, so as to make a sound; -- used
often with the reflexive; <as>as, He <ex>plopped</ex> himself into the
sofa</as>.</def> <wns>[wns=3]</wns>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> plank, flump, plonk, plunk, plump down, plunk down,
plump.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Plop
<hw>Plop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Act of plopping; the sound made in
plopping.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plot</ent>⟦br⟧
